## Java Solution

```java id="102ai"
class Solution {

    public List<List<Integer>> levelOrder(TreeNode root) {

        List<List<Integer>> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        if(root == null)
            return ans;

        Queue<TreeNode> queue = new LinkedList<>();

        queue.offer(root);

        while(!queue.isEmpty()){

            int size = queue.size();

            List<Integer> level = new ArrayList<>();

            for(int i = 0; i < size; i++){

                TreeNode current = queue.poll();

                level.add(current.val);

                if(current.left != null)
                    queue.offer(current.left);

                if(current.right != null)
                    queue.offer(current.right);
            }

            ans.add(level);
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

---

## Complexity Analysis

| Operation             | Time Complexity |
| --------------------- | --------------- |
| Visit every node once | O(n)            |

**Time Complexity:** `O(n)`

Reason:

* Every node is inserted into the queue exactly once.
* Every node is removed from the queue exactly once.

---

**Space Complexity:** `O(n)`

Reason:

* In the worst case, the queue stores all nodes of one level.

---

## Key Learning

* BFS uses a **Queue**.
* Queue follows **FIFO (First In First Out)**.
* Process the tree **level by level**.
* The line:

```java
int size = queue.size();
```

is the key to separating one level from the next.

* Each level is stored as a separate list.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting to handle an empty tree.

Always write:

```java id="102aj"
if(root == null)
    return ans;
```

---

❌ Not storing the queue size before the loop.

Wrong:

```java id="102ak"
while(!queue.isEmpty()){
    ...
}
```

If you don't store the size first, newly added child nodes will also be processed in the same level.

Always write:

```java id="102al"
int size = queue.size();
```

---

❌ Using recursion (DFS).

This problem specifically requires **level-by-level traversal**, so **BFS + Queue** is the most natural approach.

---

❌ Forgetting to check for null children.

Always write:

```java id="102am"
if(current.left != null)
    queue.offer(current.left);

if(current.right != null)
    queue.offer(current.right);
```

---

## Pattern Recognition

Whenever a problem asks for:

* Level Order Traversal
* Level by Level processing
* Breadth First Search
* Shortest distance in an unweighted tree/graph
* Nodes at each level

Think:

```text id="102an"
Queue + BFS
```

---

## Difference Between DFS and BFS

| DFS                          | BFS                   |
| ---------------------------- | --------------------- |
| Uses Recursion / Stack       | Uses Queue            |
| Goes deep first              | Goes level by level   |
| Preorder, Inorder, Postorder | Level Order Traversal |

---

## Takeaway

The key idea of Level Order Traversal is to use **Breadth-First Search (BFS)** with a **Queue**. Before processing each level, store the current queue size to know exactly how many nodes belong to that level. Process those nodes, add their children to the queue, and store each level separately. This results in an efficient **O(n)** solution and forms the foundation for many BFS-based Binary Tree interview problems.
